ce:section.ce:para:
For composites systems, during the thermo-mechanical consolidation, grain growth plays an essential role in redistribution of the reinforcement [11,47]. Two mechanisms, namely grain rotation-induced grain aggregation and GB migration, jointly control grain growth [6]. However, when the grain size exceeds 0.1 μm, grain rotation-induced grain aggregation becomes negligible and GB migration will dominate the grain growth, as schematically shown in Fig. 8
                        . It is believed that during GB migration, CPDs particles initially located in GB would separate from the moving GB and thus rearrange into the grain interior. In that case, the separation process is synergistically determined by the Zener pinning force related to particles, the driving force for grain boundary migration, and the relative mobility of GB and particles (Fig. 9
                        ) [48].
